9.	Different parameters passed to certain TF resources (Ex: Azure VM, VPC, Subnet or AWS EC2, S3, etc)

Got it ‚Äî sounds like the interviewer is checking if you understand how Terraform parameters (arguments) vary between different cloud provider resources and can map them to real-world infrastructure objects like Azure VM, VNet, Subnet, AWS EC2, S3, etc.
I‚Äôll break it down for you in a clear, structured way ‚Äî both for Azure and AWS, with examples.

1. Terraform Parameters for Azure Resources
Azure Virtual Machine (azurerm_virtual_machine or azurerm_linux_virtual_machine)
Key Parameters:
name ‚Äî VM name
location ‚Äî Azure region (eastus, westeurope)
resource_group_name ‚Äî Name of the Azure Resource Group
size ‚Äî VM size (Standard_DS1_v2)
network_interface_ids ‚Äî NICs attached
os_disk ‚Äî Block for OS disk settings
name
caching
storage_account_type
source_image_reference ‚Äî OS image settings
publisher, offer, sku, version
admin_username / admin_password or admin_ssh_key
Azure VNet (azurerm_virtual_network)
Key Parameters:
name ‚Äî VNet name
address_space ‚Äî CIDR block(s) (["10.0.0.0/16"])
location ‚Äî Azure region
resource_group_name ‚Äî Resource Group name
Azure Subnet (azurerm_subnet)
Key Parameters:
name ‚Äî Subnet name
resource_group_name
virtual_network_name ‚Äî VNet it belongs to
address_prefixes ‚Äî CIDR block(s) (["10.0.1.0/24"])

2. Terraform Parameters for AWS Resources
AWS EC2 Instance (aws_instance)
Key Parameters:
ami ‚Äî AMI ID (ami-0abcdef1234567890)
instance_type ‚Äî e.g., t2.micro
key_name ‚Äî SSH key pair name
subnet_id ‚Äî Subnet in which to launch
vpc_security_group_ids ‚Äî Security Groups
associate_public_ip_address ‚Äî Boolean
tags ‚Äî Key-value metadata
AWS S3 Bucket (aws_s3_bucket)
Key Parameters:
bucket ‚Äî Name of the bucket
acl ‚Äî Access control (private, public-read)
versioning ‚Äî Block for versioning settings
server_side_encryption_configuration ‚Äî SSE settings
lifecycle_rule ‚Äî Retention/transition rules
AWS VPC (aws_vpc)
Key Parameters:
cidr_block ‚Äî CIDR range (10.0.0.0/16)
enable_dns_support ‚Äî Boolean
enable_dns_hostnames ‚Äî Boolean
tags ‚Äî Metadata
AWS Subnet (aws_subnet)
Key Parameters:
vpc_id ‚Äî ID of parent VPC
cidr_block ‚Äî Subnet CIDR
availability_zone ‚Äî e.g., us-east-1a
map_public_ip_on_launch ‚Äî Boolean

3. How to Answer in an Interview
If asked:
‚ÄúWhat parameters are passed to certain Terraform resources like Azure VM, VPC, Subnet or AWS EC2, S3?‚Äù
You can respond:
‚ÄúIt depends on the resource type and provider, but generally each Terraform resource has arguments that define its configuration.
For example, an Azure VM (azurerm_linux_virtual_machine) needs parameters like name, location, resource_group_name, size, network_interface_ids, and source_image_reference.
An Azure VNet has address_space and location. In AWS, an aws_instance needs ami, instance_type, and networking parameters, while an S3 bucket has parameters like bucket, acl, versioning, and lifecycle rules.
Each parameter maps directly to the provider‚Äôs API settings.‚Äù

